Here's a C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:
```
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <vector>
#include <unordered_map>

int main() {
    std::string word_to_count;
    std::cout << "Enter the word to count: ";
    std::cin >> word_to_count;

    std::ifstream input_file("input.txt");
    if (!input_file) {
        std::cerr << "Error opening the input file." << std::endl;
        return 1;
    }

    std::string line;
    std::unordered_map<std::string, int> word_counts;

    while (std::getline(input_file, line)) {
        ++word_counts[line];
    }

    input_file.close();

    std::cout << "Word \"" << word_to_count << "\": " << word_counts[word_to_count] << " times." << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```
This program first asks the user to enter the word to count. Then, it opens the input file "input.txt" and reads each line. For each line, it increments the count of the line in the `word_counts` unordered map. Finally, it outputs the count of the specified word.

