You can implement a program to find common elements in two arrays by using two nested loops and a flag variable to keep track of the common elements. Here's a C++ program that demonstrates this approach:
```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

// Function to find common elements in two arrays
vector<int> findCommonElements(vector<int> arr1, vector<int> arr2) {
    vector<int> commonElements;
    bool found = false;

    for (int i = 0; i < arr1.size(); ++i) {
        found = false;
        for (int j = 0; j < arr2.size(); ++j) {
            if (arr1[i] == arr2[j]) {
                commonElements.push_back(arr1[i]);
                found = true;
                break;
            }
        }
        if (!found) {
            break;
        }
    }
    return commonElements;
}

int main() {
    vector<int> arr1 = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
    vector<int> arr2 = {3, 4, 5, 6, 7};

    vector<int> commonElements = findCommonElements(arr1, arr2);
    for (int elem : commonElements) {
        cout << elem << " ";
    }
    return 0;
}
```
In this program, the function `findCommonElements` takes two integer arrays as input and returns a vector of common elements. The function uses two nested loops, one for each array, to iterate through the elements. It uses a flag variable `found` to keep track of whether a common element has been found. If a common element is found, it's added to the `commonElements` vector and the inner loop breaks to avoid searching the same element again. If the outer loop completes without finding a common element, it breaks and returns an empty vector.
